WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.386 --> 00:00:02.803
(soft music)

2
00:00:07.950 --> 00:00:08.970
<v Dr. Weismiller>Dr. Blackwelder</v>

3
00:00:08.970 --> 00:00:10.140
is an Associate Professor

4
00:00:10.140 --> 00:00:12.543
and the Director of Geriatric Education.

5
00:00:12.543 --> 00:00:15.120
He's also the Director of Community Geriatrics

6
00:00:15.120 --> 00:00:17.940
at the Medical University of South Carolina.

7
00:00:17.940 --> 00:00:20.160
And he is going to begin a series

8
00:00:20.160 --> 00:00:25.160
of three presentations on caring for those who are maturing.

9
00:00:25.980 --> 00:00:28.140
Thank you very much, sir. I appreciate you being here.

10
00:00:28.140 --> 00:00:29.540
<v ->Thank you. Dr. Weismiller.</v>

11
00:00:30.480 --> 00:00:34.740
So I'm Russ Blackwelder, thank you for your attention.

12
00:00:34.740 --> 00:00:39.740
If you only see pregnant women

13
00:00:42.060 --> 00:00:46.383
or if you only see pediatric patients,

14
00:00:48.180 --> 00:00:49.983
anybody in the room that applies to?

15
00:00:52.320 --> 00:00:56.493
Then that means we have a room full of geriatricians,

16
00:00:58.410 --> 00:01:00.723
'cause that's who we're seeing, right?

17
00:01:01.650 --> 00:01:03.423
Dr. Weismiller has a good quote,

18
00:01:04.267 --> 00:01:05.640
I don't know if this is his original saying

19
00:01:05.640 --> 00:01:07.770
or if he took it from somebody,

20
00:01:07.770 --> 00:01:11.670
but "a good geriatrician stops more medications

21
00:01:11.670 --> 00:01:12.747
than they start."

22
00:01:14.730 --> 00:01:17.490
I mean, that sums up my three lectures.

23
00:01:17.490 --> 00:01:20.070
Okay, so nothing to disclose.

24
00:01:20.070 --> 00:01:23.430
I am at the Medical University of South Carolina

25
00:01:23.430 --> 00:01:25.980
where my practice is in

26
00:01:25.980 --> 00:01:27.480
what has traditionally been

27
00:01:27.480 --> 00:01:30.780
called a continuing care retirement community.

28
00:01:30.780 --> 00:01:33.660
So we have independent living, assisted living,

29
00:01:33.660 --> 00:01:38.660
we have long-term care, we have rehab, short stay rehab,

30
00:01:39.270 --> 00:01:41.850
and now our group goes to four of these places

31
00:01:41.850 --> 00:01:42.683
and we're growing.

32
00:01:42.683 --> 00:01:45.640
So I do geriatrics on steroids

33
00:01:46.860 --> 00:01:48.390
and we have medical students

34
00:01:48.390 --> 00:01:51.270
and our family medicine residents rotate with us.

35
00:01:51.270 --> 00:01:55.680
And since 2015, since we started,

36
00:01:55.680 --> 00:01:59.943
we've had nine graduates go on to do geriatric fellowship.

37
00:02:01.080 --> 00:02:02.430
Which is pretty impressive

38
00:02:02.430 --> 00:02:05.400
because this year in the match for geriatrics,

39
00:02:05.400 --> 00:02:09.213
they only filled something like 27% of the spots.

40
00:02:11.940 --> 00:02:14.880
So whether you like it or not, you're a geriatrician.

41
00:02:14.880 --> 00:02:18.390
Okay, so let's start off with a case.

42
00:02:18.390 --> 00:02:21.120
We have an 82-year-old couple comes to your office

43
00:02:21.120 --> 00:02:24.840
for counsel regarding their living situation.

44
00:02:24.840 --> 00:02:26.730
One of them has advanced cancer

45
00:02:26.730 --> 00:02:29.640
and is ready for additional care either in the home

46
00:02:29.640 --> 00:02:31.320
or in a facility.

47
00:02:31.320 --> 00:02:34.803
They want to know what their Medicare will cover.

48
00:02:37.740 --> 00:02:39.840
These questions will be on the board exam.

49
00:02:41.004 --> 00:02:44.049
The healthcare policy, what covers what?

50
00:02:44.049 --> 00:02:45.810
So which of the following is not true?

51
00:02:45.810 --> 00:02:47.430
People often have to pay out of pocket

52
00:02:47.430 --> 00:02:49.590
for assisted living and long-term care.

53
00:02:49.590 --> 00:02:50.910
Average cost in the US

54
00:02:50.910 --> 00:02:53.010
of a private long-term care room is

55
00:02:53.010 --> 00:02:55.740
over a hundred thousand dollars per year.

56
00:02:55.740 --> 00:02:58.020
Medicare will pay once a medical need

57
00:02:58.020 --> 00:03:00.960
for services is clearly documented.

58
00:03:00.960 --> 00:03:03.390
And D, Medicaid is the only health insurance

59
00:03:03.390 --> 00:03:05.193
that pays residential care costs.

60
00:03:12.180 --> 00:03:17.180
Yeah, C. Some of you answered D, maybe you were thinking

61
00:03:20.430 --> 00:03:25.290
maybe Tricare would cover something.

62
00:03:25.290 --> 00:03:28.770
They do cover some long-term care,

63
00:03:28.770 --> 00:03:30.543
but C, Medicare will pay.

64
00:03:33.180 --> 00:03:35.880
That's not true. Medicare will not pay any long-term care

65
00:03:35.880 --> 00:03:37.650
or assisted living cost.

66
00:03:37.650 --> 00:03:39.300
Medicare, we'll get to this in a second,

67
00:03:39.300 --> 00:03:41.850
will pay for short stay rehab.

68
00:03:41.850 --> 00:03:44.200
We'll get to the criteria for that in a second.

69
00:03:46.290 --> 00:03:49.710
Otherwise, most folks, if they have a health insurance

70
00:03:49.710 --> 00:03:53.790
that's paying for residential care cost

71
00:03:53.790 --> 00:03:55.863
are likely using Medicaid.

72
00:03:56.820 --> 00:04:01.110
Okay. Private insurance for long-term care insurance,

73
00:04:01.110 --> 00:04:04.350
that was a big product 20 years ago or so.

74
00:04:04.350 --> 00:04:07.800
They made a lot of actuarial mistakes with that.

75
00:04:07.800 --> 00:04:10.740
So it's a pretty tough product to get anymore.

76
00:04:10.740 --> 00:04:13.290
Not quite as good of a product as it used to be for folks.

77
00:04:13.290 --> 00:04:17.820
So Medicare Part A, that covers skilled nursing,

78
00:04:17.820 --> 00:04:22.820
short stay rehab, home health, hospice

79
00:04:23.220 --> 00:04:24.480
and hospital.

80
00:04:24.480 --> 00:04:26.223
Okay, that's Part A.

81
00:04:28.590 --> 00:04:29.730
For skilled nursing,

82
00:04:29.730 --> 00:04:34.730
for somebody to go, let's say they're in the hospital,

83
00:04:34.830 --> 00:04:38.703
they have a qualifying stay and then they go to rehab.

84
00:04:39.840 --> 00:04:44.070
This changes depending on the type of Medicare somebody has,

85
00:04:44.070 --> 00:04:48.330
but typically that covers full price for that rehab,

86
00:04:48.330 --> 00:04:50.373
days one through 20.

87
00:04:51.330 --> 00:04:54.690
And Medicare is paying a per diem to the facility

88
00:04:54.690 --> 00:04:57.210
and everything comes out of that per diem,

89
00:04:57.210 --> 00:05:01.410
therapy costs, medications, food, nursing care.

90
00:05:01.410 --> 00:05:04.417
Then days 21 through 100,

91
00:05:05.430 --> 00:05:08.370
the person either has a copay of 20%

92
00:05:08.370 --> 00:05:10.770
or if they have a secondary insurance

93
00:05:10.770 --> 00:05:12.483
that oftentimes picks that up.

94
00:05:13.470 --> 00:05:18.210
Okay? If you have any residents in here,

95
00:05:18.210 --> 00:05:20.512
folks that just recently graduated,

96
00:05:20.512 --> 00:05:22.800
this applies to those people you sit

97
00:05:22.800 --> 00:05:24.030
and you wait for the person

98
00:05:24.030 --> 00:05:26.610
to leave the hospital to go to rehab.

99
00:05:26.610 --> 00:05:28.251
When they finally get there,

100
00:05:28.251 --> 00:05:30.360
that's what this applies to. Okay?

101
00:05:30.360 --> 00:05:32.640
That mythical rehab place,

102
00:05:32.640 --> 00:05:34.860
the patient never seems to get to.

103
00:05:34.860 --> 00:05:36.030
Hospice, also Part A.

104
00:05:36.030 --> 00:05:39.090
Life expectancy six months or less,

105
00:05:39.090 --> 00:05:41.163
that's also paid in a per diem.

106
00:05:42.330 --> 00:05:45.480
Really nice benefit for, there was a study a few years ago

107
00:05:45.480 --> 00:05:48.660
that even depression rates for family members

108
00:05:48.660 --> 00:05:52.260
of the deceased were lower if they had hospice.

109
00:05:52.260 --> 00:05:54.600
Because hospice will provide bereavement services

110
00:05:54.600 --> 00:05:59.493
for 11 months after that loved one away, okay?

111
00:06:01.800 --> 00:06:04.860
Part B, Part B covers all their outpatient office visits,

112
00:06:04.860 --> 00:06:07.503
ambulance and DME equipment.

113
00:06:11.010 --> 00:06:16.010
Part C, usually these are managed care plans

114
00:06:16.440 --> 00:06:19.590
like Medicare Advantage, those type of things.

115
00:06:19.590 --> 00:06:23.760
Traditional Medicare doesn't cover vision or dental.

116
00:06:23.760 --> 00:06:26.310
For a lot of Medicare Advantage plans,

117
00:06:26.310 --> 00:06:27.513
they'll include that.

118
00:06:28.530 --> 00:06:31.230
They might have silver sneakers benefits, you know,

119
00:06:31.230 --> 00:06:32.940
gym memberships, those type of things

120
00:06:32.940 --> 00:06:34.540
that potentially people can get.

121
00:06:35.700 --> 00:06:38.940
Also, if you have patients come in who are just turning 65

122
00:06:38.940 --> 00:06:41.850
and they ask you, you know, we've got all these tons

123
00:06:41.850 --> 00:06:42.930
of Medicare plans

124
00:06:42.930 --> 00:06:44.493
and options to sign up for.

125
00:06:45.930 --> 00:06:47.640
If they can afford it,

126
00:06:47.640 --> 00:06:52.023
it's probably best to get the best plan they can get,

127
00:06:52.920 --> 00:06:55.560
because it's much harder as you get older

128
00:06:55.560 --> 00:06:58.680
to increase your level of coverage.

129
00:06:58.680 --> 00:07:01.200
You've gotta go through extra steps

130
00:07:01.200 --> 00:07:03.840
to get a quote/unquote, "better plan."

131
00:07:03.840 --> 00:07:05.493
Much easier to drop.

132
00:07:06.360 --> 00:07:08.010
So if people ever come in

133
00:07:08.010 --> 00:07:10.860
and want your advice on that, tell 'em

134
00:07:10.860 --> 00:07:12.810
to go as big as they can.

135
00:07:12.810 --> 00:07:14.460
That'll help 'em in the long run.

136
00:07:16.440 --> 00:07:20.403
And then of course D, D is easy. D is for drugs. Okay?

137
00:07:25.770 --> 00:07:28.770
Medicaid varies state to state

138
00:07:28.770 --> 00:07:31.950
based on modified adjusted gross income.

139
00:07:31.950 --> 00:07:33.480
Good many folks have Medicare

140
00:07:33.480 --> 00:07:36.393
and Medicaid as they get older.

141
00:07:39.660 --> 00:07:40.860
Now our next question, you're called

142
00:07:40.860 --> 00:07:45.780
to admit an 85-year-old man for UTI by the emergency room.

143
00:07:45.780 --> 00:07:47.160
His daughter is present

144
00:07:47.160 --> 00:07:50.970
and asked about placement to a skilled nursing facility.

145
00:07:50.970 --> 00:07:52.770
To qualify for skilled nursing,

146
00:07:52.770 --> 00:07:56.073
the patient must meet which criteria?

147
00:07:57.000 --> 00:07:59.373
Inpatient status, admitted for two nights.

148
00:08:00.540 --> 00:08:02.940
By being admitted to the hospital, he qualifies.

149
00:08:03.840 --> 00:08:05.070
Observation status

150
00:08:05.070 --> 00:08:07.680
and admitted for at least three nights.

151
00:08:07.680 --> 00:08:10.440
Or D inpatient status

152
00:08:10.440 --> 00:08:13.203
and admitted for at least three nights.

153
00:08:18.300 --> 00:08:19.470
So let's see how we did.

154
00:08:19.470 --> 00:08:21.390
This is gonna shock you, but this is clear as mud.

155
00:08:21.390 --> 00:08:23.340
Oh, y'all did pretty well. That's good.

156
00:08:24.570 --> 00:08:26.193
Here's why this is clear as mud.

157
00:08:27.600 --> 00:08:31.440
If you read the Medicare guidelines,

158
00:08:31.440 --> 00:08:35.320
it says you can qualify if your inpatient status

159
00:08:36.510 --> 00:08:39.633
and you're in the hospital for three days.

160
00:08:41.880 --> 00:08:44.740
Hold on. But the day

161
00:08:46.388 --> 00:08:49.088
of discharge doesn't count as one of those three days.

162
00:08:51.150 --> 00:08:54.450
So effectively you have to be there for three midnights.

163
00:08:54.450 --> 00:08:56.050
I wish they could just say that,

164
00:08:57.780 --> 00:08:59.910
but that's how you interpret it.

165
00:08:59.910 --> 00:09:01.320
Okay? Which is tough

166
00:09:01.320 --> 00:09:04.770
because to qualify for inpatient status, that's somebody

167
00:09:04.770 --> 00:09:07.410
that you expect to be there at least two midnights.

168
00:09:07.410 --> 00:09:09.630
So those don't really add up, right?

169
00:09:09.630 --> 00:09:11.080
Those don't match each other.

170
00:09:11.970 --> 00:09:14.820
There's always legislation percolating around to get rid

171
00:09:14.820 --> 00:09:17.160
of inpatient and observation status.

172
00:09:17.160 --> 00:09:18.773
That hasn't happened yet. Okay?

173
00:09:23.460 --> 00:09:25.800
All right. Now we've got an 80-year-old man referred

174
00:09:25.800 --> 00:09:28.350
for evaluation, possible depression,

175
00:09:28.350 --> 00:09:30.120
accompanied by his wife,

176
00:09:30.120 --> 00:09:33.060
who describes how much more difficulty ambulating he's had

177
00:09:33.060 --> 00:09:37.369
since he had an esophagectomy for cancer 18 months ago.

178
00:09:37.369 --> 00:09:41.520
Medications include hydrochlorothiazide, lisinopril,

179
00:09:41.520 --> 00:09:44.433
risperidone, metoclopramide, and valproate.

180
00:09:45.704 --> 00:09:50.220
On exam, flat affect, blinks little rocks slowly back

181
00:09:50.220 --> 00:09:52.230
and forth in his chair when asked to stand

182
00:09:52.230 --> 00:09:55.803
but unable to propel himself to a standing position.

183
00:09:56.640 --> 00:09:59.010
When helped up to a standing position,

184
00:09:59.010 --> 00:10:01.230
he has trouble initiating his gait,

185
00:10:01.230 --> 00:10:03.813
takes a few small steps and freezes.

186
00:10:05.370 --> 00:10:08.220
You've got that picture of a person, they're in your office

187
00:10:08.220 --> 00:10:10.260
with the wife to see you.

188
00:10:10.260 --> 00:10:12.393
Which of those is gonna be your next step?

189
00:10:17.970 --> 00:10:20.100
Yeah, there you go. Remember that.

190
00:10:20.100 --> 00:10:22.110
The next thing is board review questions

191
00:10:22.110 --> 00:10:24.753
for geriatrics are usually pretty straightforward.

192
00:10:26.910 --> 00:10:31.139
And again, good geriatrician stops more than they start.

193
00:10:31.139 --> 00:10:33.030
This person's having signs of Parkinsonism,

194
00:10:33.030 --> 00:10:35.250
largely because of all of these medicines

195
00:10:35.250 --> 00:10:37.143
which can contribute to that. Okay?

196
00:10:40.710 --> 00:10:44.580
So here's some Parkinsonism pearls, you know,

197
00:10:44.580 --> 00:10:47.430
don't overlook the medicines they could be

198
00:10:47.430 --> 00:10:48.813
causing this side effect.

199
00:10:49.680 --> 00:10:52.710
Atypical antipsychotics are big culprits.

200
00:10:52.710 --> 00:10:55.470
And if you get a board exam question,

201
00:10:55.470 --> 00:10:57.350
we'll get to this later.

202
00:10:57.350 --> 00:11:00.600
I mean the right answer is for this to say,

203
00:11:00.600 --> 00:11:04.290
really bad agitation in a demented patient,

204
00:11:04.290 --> 00:11:06.780
we want avoid antipsychotics.

205
00:11:06.780 --> 00:11:08.880
We'll get to that later, right?

206
00:11:08.880 --> 00:11:10.980
But real life isn't black and white.

207
00:11:10.980 --> 00:11:13.320
So let's say you've got a person admitted

208
00:11:13.320 --> 00:11:16.290
with Lewy body dementia and they're pulling out lines

209
00:11:16.290 --> 00:11:19.890
and throwing knives and all kind of crazy stuff, right,

210
00:11:19.890 --> 00:11:22.140
that we've gotta control. People aren't safe.

211
00:11:23.520 --> 00:11:24.353
The right answer,

212
00:11:24.353 --> 00:11:25.740
this would be a really good board exam question,

213
00:11:25.740 --> 00:11:27.360
and you have to use an antipsychotic,

214
00:11:27.360 --> 00:11:29.210
which one is gonna be the safest one?

215
00:11:30.600 --> 00:11:32.403
Probably Quetiapine.

216
00:11:33.600 --> 00:11:35.820
I mean you see the others on there.

217
00:11:35.820 --> 00:11:40.820
Pimavanserin is FDA approved for Parkinsonism,

218
00:11:41.040 --> 00:11:43.140
hallucinations and psychosis.

219
00:11:43.140 --> 00:11:46.110
Cost would be a factor.

220
00:11:46.110 --> 00:11:49.260
And then clozapine also potentially is a choice,

221
00:11:49.260 --> 00:11:52.170
but then you've gotta be signed up for the REMS program

222
00:11:52.170 --> 00:11:54.270
to be able to prescribe that.

223
00:11:54.270 --> 00:11:59.040
So less extrapyramidal side effects

224
00:11:59.040 --> 00:12:00.590
with those three at the bottom.

225
00:12:03.240 --> 00:12:07.233
More pearls. These are symptoms.

226
00:12:08.400 --> 00:12:09.570
Things that you'll see.

227
00:12:09.570 --> 00:12:12.270
Another common thing in our facility

228
00:12:12.270 --> 00:12:14.100
that people say that really tips us off

229
00:12:14.100 --> 00:12:16.680
or you know, if they're walking into your exam room

230
00:12:16.680 --> 00:12:19.050
and they get to the threshold of the door

231
00:12:19.050 --> 00:12:20.940
or they get to the threshold of an elevator

232
00:12:20.940 --> 00:12:22.770
or those kind of things and they have just a tough time

233
00:12:22.770 --> 00:12:27.770
crossing that threshold, that's associated with Parkinson's.

234
00:12:27.870 --> 00:12:32.613
Okay? Has your voice changed over the past few months?

235
00:12:33.960 --> 00:12:38.029
Okay. Get really tired walking to the mailbox.

236
00:12:38.029 --> 00:12:40.440
These type of things. Really, you know,

237
00:12:40.440 --> 00:12:42.900
I've had people before, they love writing thank you letters

238
00:12:42.900 --> 00:12:45.150
and Christmas cards and now they can't do that

239
00:12:45.150 --> 00:12:47.250
because handwriting is so hard for them,

240
00:12:47.250 --> 00:12:50.340
or they write so small people can't read it.

241
00:12:50.340 --> 00:12:51.590
All those type of things.

242
00:12:54.120 --> 00:12:55.500
'Cause we can potentially help somebody.

243
00:12:55.500 --> 00:12:58.286
This is something that we can do as we put in

244
00:12:58.286 --> 00:12:59.700
that neurology referral and those type of things is go ahead

245
00:12:59.700 --> 00:13:03.450
and potentially start treatment on carbidopa/levodopa

246
00:13:03.450 --> 00:13:05.643
and see if somebody gets a benefit from it.

247
00:13:07.200 --> 00:13:09.120
There you see some things to take home

248
00:13:09.120 --> 00:13:12.873
and could be on your board exam to help folks.

249
00:13:15.150 --> 00:13:19.140
Carbidopa/levodopa is the most effective for older adults

250
00:13:19.140 --> 00:13:21.317
for those symptoms.

251
00:13:21.317 --> 00:13:23.550
There are very few things in medicine

252
00:13:23.550 --> 00:13:26.583
where folks will hug our necks.

253
00:13:28.019 --> 00:13:30.000
This is potentially one of 'em

254
00:13:30.000 --> 00:13:32.760
if you help somebody 'cause they get on treatment

255
00:13:32.760 --> 00:13:34.543
and it really, really helps them

256
00:13:34.543 --> 00:13:35.490
and they feel so much better

257
00:13:36.960 --> 00:13:38.610
and they think you're a magician.

258
00:13:39.750 --> 00:13:42.213
That's nice. Okay.

259
00:13:43.599 --> 00:13:48.599
So what we want to watch against is using things

260
00:13:49.500 --> 00:13:52.770
like dopamine agonist and some of these other things

261
00:13:52.770 --> 00:13:55.470
that are commonly used for Parkinsonism.

262
00:13:55.470 --> 00:13:57.060
Different thing if you're treating somebody

263
00:13:57.060 --> 00:13:59.973
who's 50 years old versus somebody who's 85.

264
00:14:01.440 --> 00:14:05.302
Okay? My third lecture is gonna get into why that matters

265
00:14:05.302 --> 00:14:08.313
in drugs and how they affect older adults.

266
00:14:11.730 --> 00:14:13.080
I tell our medical students,

267
00:14:13.080 --> 00:14:15.660
whenever I ask a question, no matter what it is,

268
00:14:15.660 --> 00:14:18.210
just go ahead and say anticholinergic side effects.

269
00:14:19.110 --> 00:14:21.513
That's probably the right answer. Okay?

270
00:14:22.380 --> 00:14:23.430
Same principles here.

271
00:14:26.430 --> 00:14:28.080
All right. You see an 80-year-old female complains

272
00:14:28.080 --> 00:14:29.430
of difficulty getting comfortable

273
00:14:29.430 --> 00:14:30.720
and sleeping at night.

274
00:14:30.720 --> 00:14:33.540
On exam, you find the patient's nail beds

275
00:14:33.540 --> 00:14:36.243
appearing like the following image.

276
00:14:38.370 --> 00:14:41.040
Okay? Tough time, getting comfortable at night.

277
00:14:41.040 --> 00:14:42.273
There's the nail beds.

278
00:14:44.130 --> 00:14:45.600
Treatment of which of the following is likely

279
00:14:45.600 --> 00:14:47.340
to relieve the patient's symptoms,

280
00:14:47.340 --> 00:14:48.990
including the shape of the nails.

281
00:14:54.180 --> 00:14:56.190
Yeah, very nice. Presumably that patient was complaining

282
00:14:56.190 --> 00:14:59.130
of restless leg syndrome associated with iron deficiency.

283
00:14:59.130 --> 00:15:02.370
You fix the iron deficiency, you can fix the restless legs,

284
00:15:02.370 --> 00:15:05.340
which is wonderful because the treatment options aren't

285
00:15:05.340 --> 00:15:08.343
that great in older adults. Okay?

286
00:15:11.130 --> 00:15:13.200
Now we've got an 87-year-old nursing home resident

287
00:15:13.200 --> 00:15:14.370
returns from the hospital

288
00:15:14.370 --> 00:15:15.840
after treatment for a wrist fracture

289
00:15:15.840 --> 00:15:18.876
where she was also treated for a UTI.

290
00:15:18.876 --> 00:15:22.200
Completed course of antibiotics and takes PRN oxycodone

291
00:15:22.200 --> 00:15:23.310
for pain.

292
00:15:23.310 --> 00:15:26.310
Now has frequent incontinence of small volumes

293
00:15:26.310 --> 00:15:30.780
of liquid stool, afebrile, what's your next step?

294
00:15:30.780 --> 00:15:34.830
Antibiotics, opioids, now small volumes

295
00:15:34.830 --> 00:15:36.810
of liquid stool, afebrile.

296
00:15:36.810 --> 00:15:39.060
This is a common board question.

297
00:15:39.060 --> 00:15:41.880
Patient has a fecal lith, okay?

298
00:15:41.880 --> 00:15:45.603
And that small volume of liquid stool is coming around that.

299
00:15:46.500 --> 00:15:48.800
What you really need to treat is constipation.

300
00:15:49.650 --> 00:15:50.483
Okay?

301
00:15:53.130 --> 00:15:55.860
Two days later, severe diarrhea and abdominal pain,

302
00:15:55.860 --> 00:16:00.690
temperature of 101 Fahrenheit, white counts elevated.

303
00:16:00.690 --> 00:16:04.413
You get a C.Diff., titre, positive.

304
00:16:07.080 --> 00:16:10.563
What are you gonna treat with, of those options?

305
00:16:15.840 --> 00:16:19.293
Yeah. So right now we could use vancomycin as first line,

306
00:16:20.820 --> 00:16:23.220
125 would be the right dose.

307
00:16:23.220 --> 00:16:24.120
A lot of you are thinking,

308
00:16:24.120 --> 00:16:27.540
well the IDSA also recommends fidaxomicin as first line.

309
00:16:27.540 --> 00:16:32.310
You are correct. Vancomycin is potentially an option.

310
00:16:32.310 --> 00:16:34.980
Fidaxomicin also, we have to worry about cost,

311
00:16:34.980 --> 00:16:36.430
if insurance will pay for it.

312
00:16:37.710 --> 00:16:40.644
The data suggests we probably do have lower recurrences

313
00:16:40.644 --> 00:16:44.193
and better initial treatment with fidaxomicin,

314
00:16:45.390 --> 00:16:49.350
which is bacteriocidal as opposed to vancomycin

315
00:16:49.350 --> 00:16:51.693
which is bacteria static. Okay?

316
00:16:54.660 --> 00:16:57.690
Common cause of severe irreversible loss

317
00:16:57.690 --> 00:17:00.400
of visual acuity in older adults

318
00:17:02.310 --> 00:17:04.470
is age-related macular degeneration.

319
00:17:04.470 --> 00:17:08.430
If you get a question on this, dry is more common.

320
00:17:08.430 --> 00:17:10.500
Wet is more severe.

321
00:17:10.500 --> 00:17:13.020
Wet are the patients who will go to ophthalmologist

322
00:17:13.020 --> 00:17:15.822
and get injections in their eye,

323
00:17:15.822 --> 00:17:18.783
which sounds terrible to me.

324
00:17:20.370 --> 00:17:23.940
I mean, I had LASIK surgery when I was in college

325
00:17:23.940 --> 00:17:25.890
and I went in there and they gave me a teddy bear

326
00:17:25.890 --> 00:17:27.330
and I thought, what are you doing?

327
00:17:27.330 --> 00:17:29.283
I was so glad I had that teddy bear.

328
00:17:30.600 --> 00:17:35.600
Okay, so remember this affects the central vision, okay?

329
00:17:37.620 --> 00:17:39.360
That's where the macula is.

330
00:17:39.360 --> 00:17:41.550
Ophthalmology might give them the Amsler grid

331
00:17:41.550 --> 00:17:43.560
and they'll say, call us and watch out

332
00:17:43.560 --> 00:17:47.070
when that center, all those lines in the middle get wavy.

333
00:17:47.070 --> 00:17:48.770
That's macular degeneration. Okay?

334
00:17:50.490 --> 00:17:52.620
What causes that type of vision loss?

335
00:17:52.620 --> 00:17:54.720
I made it quick 'cause the answer was on the slide,

336
00:17:54.720 --> 00:17:55.593
I realized.

337
00:17:59.460 --> 00:18:02.877
Peripherally that vision was pretty blurry

338
00:18:02.877 --> 00:18:04.777
for those of you that didn't catch it.

339
00:18:09.720 --> 00:18:12.930
Yeah. Remember macular degeneration is central,

340
00:18:12.930 --> 00:18:16.050
glaucoma is peripheral, okay?

341
00:18:16.050 --> 00:18:18.453
Macular degeneration is gonna be more common.

342
00:18:21.960 --> 00:18:25.950
Glaucoma, that's that typical optic neuropathy.

343
00:18:25.950 --> 00:18:28.230
Usually increased intraocular pressure,

344
00:18:28.230 --> 00:18:31.083
which we can measure. Okay?

345
00:18:32.550 --> 00:18:35.370
So keep in mind the differences of those two.

346
00:18:35.370 --> 00:18:37.380
Now a nurse from local assisted living calls us

347
00:18:37.380 --> 00:18:41.160
about an 88-year-old with severe wet macular degeneration.

348
00:18:41.160 --> 00:18:43.470
Patient just told the nurse about seeing shapes

349
00:18:43.470 --> 00:18:46.350
and unicorns near the doorway.

350
00:18:46.350 --> 00:18:49.597
Okay? Patient doesn't seem bothered

351
00:18:49.597 --> 00:18:52.113
and there are no other new complaints.

352
00:18:54.412 --> 00:18:57.657
Okay? What's our next step?

353
00:19:03.150 --> 00:19:06.930
Yeah, reassurance and education. This is not that uncommon.

354
00:19:06.930 --> 00:19:09.990
I'm seeing more and more patients too that will come

355
00:19:09.990 --> 00:19:12.210
to us in rehab where they move into assisted living

356
00:19:12.210 --> 00:19:14.122
and they tell me, they say, "Oh,

357
00:19:14.122 --> 00:19:18.300
I've got Charles Bonnet syndrome," which can happen in folks

358
00:19:18.300 --> 00:19:23.220
with severe vision loss. Okay? 10 to 13%.

359
00:19:23.220 --> 00:19:27.330
Think of it like a phantom limb syndrome for the eyes.

360
00:19:27.330 --> 00:19:29.940
I mean, I've had patients that say, oh yeah, really,

361
00:19:29.940 --> 00:19:32.250
unicorns and rainbows and bright lights.

362
00:19:32.250 --> 00:19:33.810
And they say, "Oh yeah, just walk through it.

363
00:19:33.810 --> 00:19:34.770
No big deal."

364
00:19:34.770 --> 00:19:35.707
I had other patient that said,

365
00:19:35.707 --> 00:19:37.380
"I look out the window and I see a bunch

366
00:19:37.380 --> 00:19:40.770
of Santa Claus people with really long beards."

367
00:19:40.770 --> 00:19:44.163
Doesn't bother 'em. Okay? Just reassurance.

368
00:19:46.647 --> 00:19:49.140
All right. Presbycusis reduction of what type

369
00:19:49.140 --> 00:19:52.800
of hearing loss? Which is also the most common type

370
00:19:52.800 --> 00:19:56.853
of hearing loss in older adults, to give you a hint.

371
00:20:02.310 --> 00:20:03.450
Yeah, higher frequencies.

372
00:20:03.450 --> 00:20:05.583
So don't yell at your older adults.

373
00:20:06.570 --> 00:20:08.490
'Cause when we yell, our voice gets higher.

374
00:20:08.490 --> 00:20:13.490
So try to talk lower. Okay? They'll hear you better.

375
00:20:13.560 --> 00:20:16.200
Now we'll get into this a little bit,

376
00:20:16.200 --> 00:20:18.450
but I mean hearing is a really big deal for older adults

377
00:20:18.450 --> 00:20:22.980
and especially for preventing cognitive impairment.

378
00:20:22.980 --> 00:20:25.620
Okay? Really, really, really need

379
00:20:25.620 --> 00:20:28.350
to be paying more attention to hearing as people get older

380
00:20:28.350 --> 00:20:31.263
'cause it's such a risk factor for developing dementia.

381
00:20:32.370 --> 00:20:34.320
All right? Now we got a 78-year-old woman,

382
00:20:34.320 --> 00:20:36.450
history of OA, comes to your office, four week history

383
00:20:36.450 --> 00:20:38.640
of early morning shoulder and hip discomfort.

384
00:20:38.640 --> 00:20:42.660
Labs are normal except the ESR of 52. Okay?

385
00:20:42.660 --> 00:20:43.833
Which is elevated.

386
00:20:46.740 --> 00:20:49.380
What rheumatologic condition associated

387
00:20:49.380 --> 00:20:53.280
with this patient's primary diagnosis is she also

388
00:20:53.280 --> 00:20:54.963
at risk of developing.

389
00:20:55.890 --> 00:20:59.430
So she had a history of OA came in with shoulder

390
00:20:59.430 --> 00:21:01.623
and hip worsening pain in the morning.

391
00:21:02.610 --> 00:21:05.340
So this is asking which one associated with

392
00:21:05.340 --> 00:21:07.860
what you think the patient has

393
00:21:07.860 --> 00:21:09.813
is she also at risk of developing?

394
00:21:15.149 --> 00:21:20.010
Yeah, very good. The one at risk of is Giant Cell Arteritis.

395
00:21:20.010 --> 00:21:24.810
It's close overlap with polymyalgia rheumatica,

396
00:21:27.660 --> 00:21:29.553
which the patient likely has.

397
00:21:30.690 --> 00:21:31.800
Rare in younger people.

398
00:21:31.800 --> 00:21:33.360
Average age is about 70.

399
00:21:33.360 --> 00:21:35.643
That bilateral aching morning stiffness,

400
00:21:37.110 --> 00:21:40.530
two of the following three that on there said rate elevated.

401
00:21:40.530 --> 00:21:42.840
This is also one of those like patient will hug you,

402
00:21:42.840 --> 00:21:45.300
they're so excited, they feel better conditions.

403
00:21:45.300 --> 00:21:47.790
Could you get 'em started on steroids,

404
00:21:47.790 --> 00:21:50.340
and they're gonna feel remarkably better.

405
00:21:50.340 --> 00:21:55.340
Okay. PMR is lower dose steroids.

406
00:21:57.690 --> 00:22:01.413
Giant Cell Arteritis is higher dose. Okay.

407
00:22:02.820 --> 00:22:04.860
If you're concerned about Giant Cell Arteritis,

408
00:22:04.860 --> 00:22:07.032
temporal arteritis, go ahead

409
00:22:07.032 --> 00:22:08.400
and start 'em on the the steroids.

410
00:22:08.400 --> 00:22:11.040
Okay. Biopsy can still be positive.

411
00:22:11.040 --> 00:22:14.853
Also, more and more centers are doing ultrasound,

412
00:22:15.960 --> 00:22:18.957
which can really save the trouble of that biopsy,

413
00:22:18.957 --> 00:22:20.700
which can be pretty disfiguring

414
00:22:20.700 --> 00:22:24.600
and it's not always easy to find somebody to do it either.

415
00:22:24.600 --> 00:22:27.903
Okay, so go ahead and get treatment started.

416
00:22:29.280 --> 00:22:31.740
Oh, I like this. I like this case discussion.

417
00:22:31.740 --> 00:22:36.740
Alright, get called from assisted living again.

418
00:22:38.850 --> 00:22:39.960
Oh, let me also say,

